Basics of dermatology

Topical medications consist of :

  • Active ingredient
  • Vehicle or base (that dissolves the Active ingredient)
  • Excipients - preservatives or emulsifiers

Creams, ointments, gels, pastes and lotions are available.

Phototherapy is given for

  • antiinflammatory or
  • pigment inducing effects.

UV-B is more effective than UV-A. Narrow ban UV-B is better than broad band UV-B.
Phototherapy is made more effetive by administration of psoralens.

Psoralens are naturally occurring phototoxic compounds that are able to enter the cell, absorb light photons, and produce a photochemical reaction that alters the function of DNA and other cell constituents.

Commonest conditions treated with phototherapy :

  • psoriasis,
  • eczema, polymorphic light eruption
  • cutaneous T-cell lymphoma and
  • vitiligo.

Usually psoriasis doesn't get infected. If infected -> Suspect immunosuppression.

Guttate psoriasis occurs with strep infection; usually seen in children and adoslescents .

Nail changes in psoriasis:

  • thimble pitting
  • Onycholysis
  • Salmon pink discolouration - oil sign

Koebner phenomenon

Also called isomorphic response as lesions have similar morphology to 'original' lesions

Other diseases showing koebner phenomenon

  • viral warts
  • Moluscum contagiosum
  • verruca vulgaris
  • [[#Lichen planus]]
  • vitiligo
  • psoriasis

LP, vitiligo and psoriasis show "true" koebner phenomenon while molluscum contagiosum and verruca vulgaris show pseudo-koebnerization. - https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553108/

[!TIP] "Koebner's Vulgar Warts Make People Very Lively"
V - verruca vulgaris and vitiligo

Triggers for psoriasis:

  • Infection
  • Lithium can worsen psoriasis
  • improves during pregnancy and worsens post partum
  • Sunlight can improve psoriasis (UVA + UVB) but in 10% , sunlight will worsen psoriasis.
  • Smoking
  • Certain drugs
  • Withdrawal of systemic steroid can cause pustular psoriasis.

There are 5 types of join inveoment in psoriasis
In 10% arthritis can precede the skin manifestations.

  • Commonest is asymmetrical oligoarthritis
  • Classical description is distal interphalangeal joints

Psoriasis is usually non pruritic.
Erythrodermic psoriasis is painful.

Cell turnover rate is not reduced in psoriasis. But proliferation rate is increased. -> hyperkeratosis.

Acitretin is not immunosuppressive

Subtypes of psoriasis

Chronic plaque psoriasis

Lichen planus

Slowly (and spontaneously) resolving T cell mediated autoimmune disease

Cause is unknown.
Typical lesions have a Violaceous / lilac colour.
intensely itchy!
Flat topped lesions.
Wickham's striae are seen in older people.

Lichen planus: described by 4 P's

  1. Pruritic - intensely
  2. Purple - violaceous - NOT salmon pink
  3. Polygonal
  4. Plaques / papules

Wickhams striae: white lace - like patterns on the surface of lesions. - but not seen in all patients. Seen in most patients.
Cutaneous wickhams is seen in all patients.
Oral wickhams striate is seen only in 50% of patients.

Affects skin, mucous membranes (especially the oral mucosa), scalp, nails, and genitalia - see UpToDate images

There are multiple variants - hypertrophic, bullous, annular etc

Pathogenesis of Lichen planus

Unknown - possible autoimmune based involving CD 8 T cells

Histology of lichen planus

Several well defined histiological findings identify lichen planus:
Hyperkeratosis without parakeratosis

  • Vacuolization of the basal layer
  • Civatte bodies (apoptotic keratinocytes) in the lower epidermis
  • Wedge-shaped hypergranulosis, "saw-tooth" shaped rete ridges
  • Small clefts at the dermal-epidermal junction (Max-Joseph spaces)
  • Band-like, lymphocytic infiltrate at the dermal-epidermal junction
  • Eosinophilic, colloid bodies (apoptotic keratinocytes) in the papillary dermis
  • Pigment incontinence (most prominent in dark-skinned individuals)

Management of lichen planus

Cutaneous lichen planus usually resolves within 2 years.
Treatment is focused on decreasing time to resolution and managing pruritis.

Local steroid, systemic steroids are the mainstay although not backed by good evidence.
Retinoids may be used.
+ other drugs

lichenoid reaction to certain drugs

Mycosis fungoides

Cutaneous T cell lymphoma - usually limited to the skin. Looks like tinea versicolor.

Q 3: Eczema

" Any type of skin inflammation - dermatitis"
Different types of eczema

  • atopic eczema - not all eczema is atopic eczema
    • Usually child hood onset, other features of atopy like hay fever
    • Has a genetic component
  • Contact dermatitis
    • Hypersensitivity to some chemical
    • Two types : Irritant _ instantaenous onset or Alergic -- delayed onset (type 4 hypersensitivity)
  • There are acute eczemas or chronic eczems
    • Acute - oozing, fissurring, secondary infection
    • chronic - itchy and lichenified (skin becomes thickened)
      Treated with topical steroid, calcinui, MTX, azathiopione, cyclosporin, moisutises, UV-A and UV-B
      Eczema herpeticum is a complication

Q 5: Urticaria

Hives;
Acute urtiacaria and chronic urticaria (> 6 weeks)
Caused by mast cell degranulation
various riggers - can be spontaneous (without any trigger; usual cause for chronic urticaria), autoimmune, chemicals, type 1 hypersensitivity

Main type of urticaria:
Physical urticaria - eg with cold (i.e cold water), sun light, exercise
Dermographism - urticaria with minor trauma ; this is the commonest type of urticaria. Harmless.
Drug triggers: Esp: Aspirin, NSAIDS, ACE inhibitors, morphine,

Immunosuppresatns like MTX and cyclosporine can be given for resistant cases.

Q 6: Erythema multiforme

Is immune mediated - circulating immune complexes deposited in blood vessels. Cell mediated immunity. Usually triggered by an ==infection== - eg herpes simplex. (hepatitis, mycoplasma, strep etc)
Annular, non scaly, plaques
Target lesions are pathognomonic
Minor and Major

  • Major involes mucosal surfaces
  • Minor - only the skin
    Palms and soles usualyl involved.
    Usually occurs in younger patients.

Usually resolves spontaneous in 1 - 2 weeks.
Management is to treat the underlying ==infection.==

Erythema multiforme is in the same spectrum as SJS or TEN. But doesn't necessarily progress to these two.
Stevens-johnson - only mucosa
TEN - mucosa + skin

Q 7: Erythema nodosum

Type 4 hypersensitivity;
There's inflammation of sub cutaneous fat. - panniculitis
There an immunological reaction : Triggered by infection / malignancy / drugs
Pathology involves small vessel vasculitis.

Causes:

  • TB

  • Streptococcal infection

  • Leprosy

    • Erythema nodosum leprosy ; painful nodules in leprosy patients; = erythema nodosum
    • Erythema nodoum leprosum <- steroid are given. (steroid aren't given for all erythema nodosum)
    • Erythema nodosum does not occur in tuberculoid leprosy.

  • Mycoplasma / fungal infection - histoplasmosis

  • Systemic diseases -> Sarcoidosis, behcet, inflammatory bowel disease

  • Drugs: sulphonamides, OCP

  • Pregnancy

Commonest : anterior shins ; heals without scarring, it never ulcerates.
Treatment: Treat the underlying cause.
Systemic steroid are usually not indicated unless for resistant cases.

Q 8: Vasculitis

Typically presents as painful, palbable, non blanching purpura.
HSP is a small vessel vasculitis (T)
Cryogolbulinaemia is a cause of vasculitis.
Dapsone is a treatment in selected cases.
Urticarial vasculitisi is a small vessel vasulitis. Lesions persist for more than 24 hours.

There is some classifcation of panniculitis based on presense / absense of vasculitis.

Pemphigoid: tense blisters: dermo-epidermoid junction involved; usually occurs in elderly
Immune complexes seen at the dermo-epidermal junction.

Rare, life threatening

Nikolsky sign +ve

Rarer than pemphigus vulgaris. No oral lesions.

Bullous pemphigoid

Occurs over 60 years of age.
Tense blisters

Linear IgA disease

Linear IgA deposition along the dermo-epidermal junction
Cause not know. Associated with vancomycin

Dermatitis herpetiformis

Cutaneous manifestation of coeliac disease.
Patients should avoid gluten.

Q 10: Discoid lupus erythematosus

Mostly occurs in sun exposed areas ; face, extensors.
Scarring is a feature; can cause scarring alopecia and hair loss.
only rarely progresses to SLE.
This is a rare instance where potent topical steroid are used on the face. (prevention of scarring outweighs S/E of steroids)

Q 11: Dermatomyositis

Ragged cucitles are seen; heliotrop rash, nail fold relangiectasia
Shawl sign
Gottron's papules
Calcinosis is a feature - more proximal distribution. More common in juvenile dermatomyositis.
A large percentage (30 - 40%) is associated with malignancy!
Commoner in females. Toxoplasmosis can cause a similar syndrome.

Q 12: Systemic sclerosis

Majority have ANA positive.
Most have raynaud's phenomenon
In limited SC, other organ involvement is not seen (distribution in lmited SC is below elbows, below knees etc ). But they do have inolvement of other organs.
Skin lesions can be pruritic. There is a salt and pepper appearance.
Peri ungual telengiectasia is common.

Q 13: Scabies

Face is involved only in babies as they don't have sebum on the face.

Burrows are very suggestive of scabies.
Permethrin.

Q 15: Leprosy

Tuberculoid to lepromatous is a spectrum. Lepromatous it the severe form.
Tuberculoid -> Few hypopigmented patches only and some nerve involvement.
Tuberculoid form is not infectious.
Immune suppresed persons will get lepromatous lepsory.

Lepromatous leprosy: Large number of bacilli in skin lesions; not so in tuberculoid leprosy.

Leoprosy is categorised based on number of lesions (<> 5)
Multibacillary - 12 months (rifampicin 600 monthly, clofaziime 300 monthly, dapsone daily. )
Paucibacillary - 6 months (Rifampicin 600, dapsone ?daily)
MDT treatment should not be stopped for reactions

  • type 1 reactions : exiting lesions become red and nerve reactions
  • Type 2 reactions : New lesions develop, fever, testicular pain
    These are not drug reactions; treatment is continued. (unless a drug reaction occurs)
    Temperature is the first sensation to be affected. -> Then pain
    Main route of infection is nasal droplets.
    Sometimes sensory impairment to an area may be masked because of multi sensory supply to a particular area (like the face)

Skin involvement does not always precede nerve involvement.

Lepromin skin test

Is not done now;
Even skin biopsy is not needed if clinically very suggestive of lepsory.

Erythema marginatum

Seen most commonly in early stages of acute rheumatic fever [[Bacterial pathogens#GAS]].
Middle of the lesion shows resolution. External edge is sharp, internal edge is blurred.
Present on limbs and trunk but not the face.
Also seen in hereditary angiooedema and psitaccosis. Source

Erythema mulforme

"Short lived, acute, painless, immune mediated condition. ""

90% of cases are triggered by infection; commonest is HSV infection. Mycoplasma infection is another cause.
Distribution: Extensor surfaces of the distal limbs. Rash appears in 3-5 days after the infection and spreads centripetally; dissapears in about 2 weeks.
Lesions are usually asymptomatic; itching and pain are uncommon.

[!INFO] What is Viridans group streptococci?
Large group of commensal streptococcal Gram-positive bacteria species that are α-hemolytic, producing a green coloration on blood agar plates
The term “streptococcus viridans”, refers to five groups of Streptococci that include Streptococcus anginosus group, mitis group, sanguinis group, salivarius group, and finally the mutans group

S aureus bacteriuria associated with hematuria is a feature of S aureus bacteraemia.
Hematuria in the setting of IE results from embolic renal infarction or immunologically mediated glomerulonephritis.
Think of it as a clinical syndrome of features of IE, but without positive cultures.
Up to 5% of IE is culture negative IE.

Overview of Clinical entities comprising IE

Vancomycin is slowly bactericidal - may need longer treatment course.

Gram +ve IE
  • Staph aureus - *usually not penicillin sensitive; so penicillin is not appropriate.
    • Methicillin sensitive species -> can treat with semisynthetic penicillin like nafcillin, or oxacillin.
    • If Methycillin resistant -> treat with vancomycin.
    • Add on Gentamicin should not be used as risk of renal injury outweighs benefit of combination therapy.
    • Coagulase negative staphylococci (Staph. epidermidis) - Usually they have similar sensitivity patterns to coagulase positive staph. However, they are usually methicillin resistant; so treat with vancomycin.
  • Streptococci -
  • Enterococci - IE causing enterocci are enterococcus faecalis.
    • They are resistant to many antibiotics. Vancomycin + gentamicin combination can be used because of synergistic action.
  • Gram -ve IE usually coccurs due to HACEK organisms -> Virtually all HACEK organisms are highly susceptible to third-generation cephalosporins such as ceftriaxone, even strains that produce beta-lactamase.
  • IE due to other gram -ve organisms is very rare.

Treatment generally similar to left sided IE.

Fungal infective endocarditis

Consider if culture negative endocarditis is not responding to treatment.
Fungi and gram-negative bacilli were rare causes of right-sided IE but incidence is increasing with IV drug use.
Fungal IE is associated with 67% mortality Vs. 3.6% for non fungal IE.
Indications - valve dysfunction causing heart failure, persistent infection, intracardiac abscess

The following scenarios support early valve surgery for native left-sided IE: Source

  • Signs or symptoms of heart failure as a result of valve dysfunction
  • IE caused by fungal infection or highly resistant organisms
  • IE complicated by annular abscess, heart block, or destructive perforating lesions
  • Persistent infection (bacteremia or fever; >5-7 days) after appropriate antimicrobial therapy has been initiated, if other sources of fever or infection have been ruled out
  • Recurrent emboli or persistent/growing vegetations despite appropriate antimicrobial therapy

[!TIP] Summary of indications for surgical intervention
Some type of cardiac dysfunction - haemodyanic or elecrophysiologic
Physical defect caused by the infection (abscess / perforation)
Persistent infection (either direct evidence of resistance despite therapy OR presence of typically resistant organisms (eg fungi))
Recurrent emboli / growing vegetations despite therapy

  • Amyloidosis - not super urgent
